<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-161-920  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 161 920.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  March 13 1989 n529 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to manage DOD procurement. (Department of Defense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Packard, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The major cause of problems in military acquisition is thatdefense spending has been micro-managed to death and made criminalby the combined actions of the DOD and Congress.andP;  There is norational system whereby Congress and the executive branch reachagreement on national military strategy, the forces to carry itout and the funding that should be provided.andP;  A system must beestablished that creates real incentive for better performance.andO;One option would be to go back to past contracting policies thatwould include cost as well as contracts with incentives based onperformance.andP;  The use of prototyping to provide legitimatecompetition on smaller systems and subsystems could also be used.andO;Greater use of commercial products could provide better equipmentat lower cost.andP;  Finally, a more objective way to measure theperformance of the defense contractors based on past performanceshould be established.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AttitudeDefense ContractsFraudPurchasing Systems.andO;Person:    Packard, David (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>